Barack Obama is the fourth US President to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
U.S. President Barack Obama arrives in Oslo, Norway for 26 hours, to receive the Nobel Peace Prize as the fourth U.S. president in history.
In addition, he receives the diploma, the medal and a check of $1.4 million for his extraordinary efforts to intensify world diplomacy and cooperation among peoples.
The head of the White House will arrive tomorrow with his wife Michelle in the northwestern metropolis and will be busy all the time.
First, he visits the Nobel Institute, where he meets for the first time with the five committee members who elected him in October from 172 people and 33 organizations.
The couple will meet with Norwegian King Harald V and Queen Sonja.
In the afternoon, the visit culminates with the ceremony at which Obama receives the prestigious prize.
He is the fourth President of the United States, but only the third to receive the prize directly in office.
The White House has already announced that Obama will talk about the war in Afghanistan when taking over the prize.
The president does not want to escape this topic because he knows that he is taking the prize as a president who is currently waging war in two countries.
He has reinforced the war efforts a few days ago by sending more troops to Afghanistan, which no one of his critics forgets to highlight.
At the ceremony, Obama also received the golden medal, the diploma and a check of ten million Swedish crowns (approximately 24 million Czech crowns).
He intends to donate the money to charities, but he has not yet decided on a concrete charity.
The event program then includes a banquet with the president and his wife, at which, in addition to the king and queen of Norway, the prime minister and another 250 invited guests will be present.
Obama has been very discreet about the price from the beginning.
For example, he pointed out that he felt he didn’t deserve the prize entirely.
He also repeated several times that the prize is not just for him, but for everyone who aspires to the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement, he noted that it was a “call to action” for him.
