Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It is almost strange with what student ambition Barack Obama, the president with his reputation of the smartest, repeats the strategy of his predecessor on the Afghan issue, which he considered the stupidest.
When he eventually swept out his long-awaited Afghanistan doctrine, it turned out that he had written it off on the copy paper from the Bush-Iraq scenario for three years.
Not only has he repeatedly used the phrase “as in Iraq” in the text himself, he has even used the name of the Bush Declaration of January 2007 as the name of his own declaration: “New Way Forward” without hesitation.
Three years ago, he even criticized Bush’s idea of sending fresh troops to Iraq plagued by the civil war as a “irresponsible and in its consequences catastrophic decision.”
But the following months showed that the Bush strategy based on recommendations from the military was the only possible and very successful, so that today there is no talk about Iraq in the news.
This did not improve Bush’s reputation, as he objectively left his successor in a much more grateful starting position than expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes the miracle will repeat itself.
To increase the contingent of troops, he was once again asked by the military, especially the chief commander of the Afghanistan operation General Stanley McCristal, who even despite the habits of subordination harshly criticized the roaring shooters in the White House.
He called for 40,000 troops to reverse the situation.
The president hesitated for three months, but did not come up with a better idea and so he deceived General Wenistens with 10,000 soldiers.
From Europe, he has pushed the promise for another 5,000, even though he himself initially expected at least 10,000.
The most problematic of the entire Obama strategy is his plan to withdraw the troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and complete this process within three years.
Some have doubts that the halved increase will have the same effect as the measure in Iraq.
Even despite the brotherly war of recent years, the Iraqi society is relatively well structured, its leaders respect the values.
The Afghan situation is characterized by the contraindication - no one can rely on and no agreements are held.
Under these conditions, it is difficult to prepare the Afghan security forces, who are accustomed to changing their minds every day.
The political institutions, even if they were formally established correctly, remain merely fictitious structures behind which patriarchal tribal relations will continue to grow.
The balance of interests between the different ethnic groups is unusually complicated, especially due to the ambiguity of the circumstances that further complicate the influences of Pakistan and Iran.
Even the construction of a "active state", which is the minimalist goal of the entire operation, is very unrealistic.
Time Horizon of Obama's Strategy Strangled by His Voluntaryism
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened and is now on the verge of an explosion.
Believing that the little soldiers who broke out in the cry of war about the "early return" can do a miracle here can only a truly romantic soul, not impressed by facts.
From a political point of view, setting the date for the withdrawal is pure irresponsibility, because the Taliban will take it as an indirect confession of the American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that the willingness of Europeans to participate in the fighting in Afghanistan is declining.
European politicians cannot and do not want to explain to their voters how the security of Germany or Italy is related to the war in the Hindukush suburbs.
Another possible factor that can radically affect the situation is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the heightened sanctions do not affect the Iranians, a very difficult question arises for the United States, whether the problem can not be solved with troops.
This question must be answered in the period in which America moves to a victorious withdrawal from Afghanistan after Obama.
But any solution will also mean a dramatic turning point in the Afghan situation.
The only consolation for Barack Obama is the fact that there are still three years until the presidential election, and therefore there is still enough time for him to resort to a different strategy if it turns out to be a total failure.
