Czech discovery: a substance that also works on ‘stolen’ HIV viruses
The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds designed to prevent the spread of HIV viruses in the body.
The main advantage of the enhanced substance is that it also works against the viruses that are already resistant to drugs.
This fact outweighs the disadvantage that the compound does not affect common viral variants as strongly as one of the already existing drugs.
AIDS disease cannot be cured.
However, the drug composition can prolong the life of patients and prevent the proliferation of HIV viruses in the body.
However, their intake is accompanied by a whole host of side effects.
Incomplete suppression of viral proliferation has also resulted in the development of resistant viruses against which no drugs are effective.
The work of experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences CR, the VSCHT (Chemical and Technological University) Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to deal with virus resistance.
They have demonstrated that the substances referred to as metallocarbonates act on the protein responsible for the proliferation of the HIV virus.
Metalocarbons are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block viral proliferation in different ways than all medicines used today, so they can overcome the resistance problem.
In their work, the scientists come up with new “improved” compounds, which have been prepared based on the knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the virus-protein.
The metallocarbons have a unique three-dimensional structure: two diverse cages consisting of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms, coupled by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Homogeneous and persistent virus
HIV protease is the protein of the HIV virus, which is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV virus splitting caused by the HIV protease, no mature infectious virus particles would form.
If we turn off the HIV protease, we also turn off the proliferation of the virus in the patient’s body, the scientists explain in a press release released by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences CR.
In the paper, published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, the scientists describe whole rows of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are coupled by a short organic chain, which is then systematically further altered.
