The new vaccination
Free vaccines for August children
From January, children born on August 2 last year and later can be vaccinated for free against pneumococci.
The condition is that you have not yet received a dose of the vaccine.
Those who started the vaccination last year or earlier must also pay for further re-vaccination.
The first dose of the vaccine must be given between the 3rd and 5th months of life of the child.
Last year, a quarter of families vaccinated their children against pneumococcal disease.
The parents paid 1600 crowns and more for a dose.
Four doses are required for vaccination of younger children.
Overall, experts estimate that health insurance companies spend 300,000 to 450,000 crowns per year on vaccine doses.
However, they save on the treatment that children would need without vaccination.
So far, the state has spent about 500,000 a year on all surface vaccinations of children.
Compulsory vaccination was introduced with the so-called Janota package.
Pneumococci cause middle ear inflammation, but also severe infections including cerebral dermatitis and blood poisoning.
Pneumococcal infections kill up to 28 children under 10 years of age every year in our country, after examination in hospitals.
Outside the Czech Republic, the compulsory pneumococcal vaccination of children has been introduced in about 40 countries.
Will vaccination be mandatory?
This vaccination may be mandatory in the future.
From January this will be paid by the insurance companies and will be voluntary.
That the obligatory vaccination would be better, mentioned, for example, the head of the Nahla citizens’ association, Rudolf Kalovsky.
