Can Islam be French?
Pluralism and pragmatism in a secular state.
At a time when Swiss voters have voted for a ban on building minarets and concerns about the alleged Islamization of Europe are widespread, John Bowen, an American academic, has written a well-founded and thoughtful report on whether Muslims can be integrated — and integrated — into one of Europe’s most explicitly secularized societies.
Some readers will read this new book out of admiration for the author's latest work: "Why the French Don't Like Headscarves" (2006), an elegant and dense study of a controversial issue that divided and occupied the country over a decade and a half and whose effects can still be seen today.
Bowen’s latest book offers a more comprehensive and daring spectrum.
As a good anthropologist, he wants to know not only what politicians and the media say about Islam in France, but what is really happening in the field.
He has spent months in mosques, schools and institutes that now offer the 5 to 6 million Muslims in France, as Bowen calls it "Islamic free spaces."
He is a good listener, he reflects debates between teachers and students on the issues that worry them most.
Should a Muslim marry in a mosque or a town hall (or both)?
Should young Muslims be taught about evolution and homosexual rights?
Can a Muslim woman marry a non-Muslim man?
Is it permissible for a Muslim to use a interest-oriented banking system to get a mortgage?
It is these seemingly profane matters, he claims, that make up everyday life, in contrast to the political dramas that the media occupies.
The author recognises a new generation of imams, teachers and intellectuals, none of them with a known name, possibly with the exception of Tarik Ramadan, an Arab-Muslim scholar and academic born in Switzerland.
This new generation is trying to open the debate about how it is possible to be a good Muslim and a good citizen in a modern secular society.
You don’t have all the arguments on your side.
Conservatives are suspicious of the idea of a French or European Islam.
The thinkers and activists Bowen interviewed mostly disagree with their Salafi counterparts – advocates of the purist Sunni Islam linked to Saudi Arabia – who now show a small but influential presence among Europe’s Muslims.
Bowen believes that Muslim values and French secularism could be compatible.
But an agreement requires giving and taking on both sides.
He questions how much French political decision-makers (and the intellectual elite who so passionately guard the separation of church and state) really feel committed to pluralism.
He suggests that Muslims may experience harsher treatment than Catholics, Protestants, and Jews, who in turn had to make their historical compromise with secular republicanism.
He recognises a “strengthening of the value screws” rather than a growing pragmatism.
After reading this book, one is inclined to say “Yes, but not yet.”
