Ironically, in the waters north of these two hunting nations, the ice will last the longest.
In his new book, After the Ice, Alun Anderson, a former editor of the science magazine New Scientist, offers a clear and disturbing description of Arctic science and a captivating insight into how the future could evolve.
Not that scientists have all the answers.
Neither atmospheric scientists nor oceanographers can adequately explain the speed of changes.
This is not due to a lack of explanation.
The pioneering journeys of Fridtjof Nansen at the end of the 19th and early 20th centuries made it possible for the first time to guess the twisting of the package ice.
In the Cold War, submarines moderated the shifting grades when submerged.
A useful addition are satellite measurements and the large-scale deployment of measuring probes on icebergs, but still much is achieved by fearless people camping outdoors in the cold.
Anderson takes a look into the strange, tiny world of the outflow system within the Arctic ice formed by saltwater resin salts that are compressed when frozen.
But, from the bear on the ice to the microscopically small wonders in the ice, they’re all threatened when the summer ice goes away, which is expected between 2013 and 2050.
In a few months, it could be us.
Marines were among the 6,000 who settled in Arlington.
The liberated De'Angello Robinson travelled seven hours by bus to lay a single crown on the tomb of a soldier he had never met.
For him and the other Marines who made the trip from Camp Johnson in Jacksonville, North Carolina, to the Arlington National Cemetery to decorate tombs, the day was a tribute to the men and women in whose footsteps they followed.
In a few months, no matter where we are being brought back from, we could be that, Robinson said of the fallen soldiers.
If we were, I would like someone to do the same for me, so I try to show my respect.
He was one of more than 6,000 volunteers gathered on Saturday morning to lay crowns on the graves of veterans in several sections of the Arlington Cemetery.
Morrill Worcester, owner of the Worcester Wreath Company in Harrington, Maine, founded this tradition in 1992 when he and a few others decided to decorate several hundred graves at the Arlington cemetery.
It’s now an 18-year-old tradition, and Morrill and his wife Karen, who make this trip every year, stop in different cities along the way to conduct events dedicated to people in the military and victims of terrorism.
The Worcesters also founded a non-profit organization, Wreaths Across America, which extended the event to other states.
This year, volunteers laid more than 16,000 crowns on the graves at Arlington Cemetery, in areas on the Pentagon, on graves at Fayetteville National Cemetery in Arkansas, at Battery Park in New York, and at United Airlines Flight 93 Memorial Site in Shanksville, Pennsylvania.
For the second time, the Walmart Foundation donated more than $150,000 to buy and transport the crown.
Charleen Hunt, 70, from Westminster, said she made the trip to Arlington in memory of her husband, a deceased professional soldier.
Although her husband is not buried in Arlington, Hunt said, this is her way of giving back something to those who made sacrifices.
She said this is a small contribution to how we civilians can support our soldiers.
It’s like visiting a family cemetery.
Packed in layers of warm clothes, the volunteers wandered across the vast lawns and hills of the cemetery.
The volunteers targeted older tombs from World War I and World War II and the Vietnam War, as they are not visited as often as the newer tombs, according to the organizers.
The mood was cheerful, children were playing and couples held each other by the hand as they carried the fresh pine branches to the graying tombstones.
Each round crown was dark green with a small red loop attached to the top.
Section 60, located nearby, where mostly veterans of the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan are buried, remained almost quiet.
The United Service Organizations donated 1,000 crowns to decorate this section, but the dark mood of current wars filled this area.
Some were crying openly, others were praying, and families and friends were holding together in the icy air.
Some read loudly the names carved in stone, while others bowed down to small black and white space cards that had been laid in the wet mud for those whose tombstones had not yet been finished.
Sandra Lockwood was one of many mothers who shed bitter tears in front of her son’s grave.
She is 8 hours from Zanesfield, Ohio, driving to visit the graveyard of Naval Infantry sub-officer David Shane Spicer, who fell in battle in July.
No one should ever forget why we are free ... my son paid for it, she said.
“When I’ve been away for a long time, I want someone to remember him.”
U.S. government contractors arrested by Cuban authorities
The Cuban government has arrested a U.S. government contractor who sold mobile phones and laptops in the country, State Department officials said on Saturday.
The contractor, which has not yet been identified, works for Development Alternatives Inc. based in Bethesda.
The company works on projects for clients such as USAID, the U.S. Agency for International Development and for the World Bank.
U.S. Consular Officers in Havana are trying to gain access to the prisoner who was arrested on December 5.
The specific charges have not yet been released, although according to Cuban law, a Cuban citizen or a foreign visitor can be arrested for almost anything accused of “threatening.”
All so-called counter-revolutionary activities, which include light protests and critical writings, pose a risk of arrest.
Anti-government graffiti and statements are considered serious crimes.
Cuba has a growing blogger community led by popular reporter Yoani Sánchez, who frequently describes how she and her husband are being persecuted and attacked by government officials.
Sánchez has repeatedly sought permission to leave the country to receive prizes, but this has always been rejected.
The arrest of an American contractor is likely to increase tensions between Castro’s brother’s communist government in Cuba and the Obama administration, which sought a “slow” approach to improving relations with the island.
The news of the arrest was first by the New York Times on Friday night.
The new US policy emphasizes that the United States will pay back if the Cuban government takes concrete steps in this direction, such as releasing political prisoners and creating more space for opposition.
Mobile phones and laptops are legal in Cuba, although they are new and sought after products in a country where the average earning of a government employee is $15 a month.
The Cuban government has only since this year allowed ordinary citizens to buy a mobile phone, it is mainly used for sending text messages, as a 15-minute phone call would cost a daily salary.
Internet access is extremely limited on the island.
It is available in expensive hotels and there for foreign visitors and at some government agencies, such as universities.
Cubans who want to log in often have to report their names to the government.
Access to many websites is limited.
In Cuba, the arrest of an American is rare.
Most of the few U.S. citizens imprisoned in Cuba are in prison for crimes such as drug smuggling, said Gloria Berbena, a spokeswoman for the U.S. Interest Office in Havana.
Berbena said she could not provide further information about the arrest.
The arrest and imprisonment are clearly wrong.
One activity that would be legal in any other free society – giving free mobile phones – is a crime in Cuba, said Jose Miguel Vivanco, head of the American section of the Human Rights Watch group, which recently released a harsh report on freedom in Cuba titled “New Castro, the same Cuba,” a reference to the inauguration of Raul Castro as the leader of the country, replacing the sick older brother Fidel.
Vivanco said the accused were very often arrested, convicted and imprisoned within a day.
He said that probably any solution would be political and that the Cuban government is often provoking a negative reaction in the United States, precisely at a time when the two countries are moving towards each other for more dialogue.
