As a result, they were held for days in the eastern city of Sargodha, far away from the hostile mountains in the northwest, which have become a terrorist haven.
They were seen as part of a covert operation.
That’s why they were rejected, the government official said, who wanted to remain anonymous due to the sensitivity of the matter.
The government official said the men were not at all discouraged and continued to seek the right recommendations to gain access to Al-Qaeda camps when they were arrested by Pakistani law enforcement authorities.
The case of the five men – who are still in Pakistan and being questioned by the FBI – underscores the critical role of recruiters in identifying future terrorists and, more importantly, in deciding who is trustworthy.
Since the attacks of September 11, 2001, the U.S. intelligence service has made it a matter of utmost urgency to accommodate human active posts within al-Qaeda.
The recruiters of the organization act as patrons who do not allow those whose commitment to the Holy War is not serious enough and those who could be spies.
American volunteer recruits are undergoing a special test by A.K.A., analysts said.
However, due to their potential access to U.S. targets and their propaganda value, they are also considered extremely attractive to the group.
