He then went on to Mandarin and said, “Because the venue is large, I can’t hear what’s going on outside.”
He noted that it depends on the individual’s perspective whether the demonstration would hurt or help.
It shows the focus of the general public and various sectors on the subject of climate change, he said.
On the other hand, "you can also say that they interfere with the negotiations or the freedom of other people."
Test data reveals persistent racial gap
The math performance testimonials were welcome good news for public schools in Washington D.C. last week.
Although the Washington District is still far behind the country’s highest-performing schools, testimonials show that fourth and eighth grade students have made faster progress over the past two years than cities that include Atlanta, Chicago and New York.
But what is included in the latest figures of the National Assessment of Educational Progress (NAEP) is the persistent performance gap between African-American and white students, both at local and national levels.
The average score of white fourth grade students from Washington D.C. has risen from 262 to 270 over the past two years (on a 500 scale), but that of their African American peers has risen by only three points from 209 to 212.
In reality, the performance gap increased from 53 points to 58 points between 2007 and 2009.
The progress of the African-American eight-grade remained basically the same, falling by a statistically negligible point from 245 to 244.
The average score of white students was not included in the test data because the sample scope was not large enough.
The picture over a six-year period is also not more encouraging.
The gap that separated white and black fourth-classers in 2003 when the first NAEP was recorded in that district was 60 scale points (262 to 202).
And although the score reached by the children of both groups has grown over this time period, the difference has hardly diminished with 58 points now.
Some district education advocates last week expressed concern that the outcomes celebrated by school cleric Michelle A. Rhee and Democratic Mayor Adrian M. Fenty were largely driven by white students who are already powerful children anyway.
This suggests that we have raised the overall rating by treating those at the top of the scale, which is problematic and challenging, said Jeff Smith, board member of D.C. Voice, a non-profit group advocating for education equality in Washington D.C.
I’m not jumping up and down for a range of two or three points, said Democratic Washington City Council member Kwame R. Brown, who has a daughter in the fourth grade of Eaton Elementary School.
Brown, a frequent critic of Rhee’s management style, said the message of the exam scores is that the city’s secondary schools urgently need attention.
Of course, you always want to see the positive signs, which I respect.
What scares me, however, is that we do not spend almost the time and energy we would have to spend on our high school.
Rhee said the district must continue to find better ways to meet the needs of underperforming students.
This fall, for example, some teachers will be trained to use a new reading curriculum, the Wilson Reading System, aimed at students in the upper classes of primary and secondary schools who have not mastered basic reading skills at the beginning of their school career and are significantly behind their peers.
Daily Mathematics, a curriculum that emphasizes games and real-life experiences from kindergarten to sixth grade, was brought to Washington under former senior school inspector Clifford Janey, and this curriculum attributes some of the NAEP advances last week.
I think we need to continue to work to give the best measures to benefit students who are below the grade level, Rhee said.
Others say that the NAEP results highlight the question of whether Rhee can continue to improve the overall performance of the system while continuing to provide the additional money and resources for the underperforming schools that are needed to reduce the gap.
This is a serious dilemma for Michelle Rhee, said Bruce Fuller, a professor of education at the University of California in Berkeley, who examined urban test results.
The conventional remedy is to focus its resources and management reforms on the schools located in the poorest areas of Washington D.C.
The objective could have political repercussions that work against this important item of the agenda.
The weakness is, of course, like other urban school inspectors, that she is trying to keep the white and black middle class.
Our focus is on ensuring that we build a system of great schools.
We need to strengthen our schools in the neighborhoods so that all families, no matter where they live, can be sure that their children can receive excellent public education.
Janey, who is now a school inspector in Newark, said in an interview this week that one of the most significant elements to close the performance gap is to extend the traditional public school year, which is currently 180 days in Washington, to compete with the charter schools.
One has to increase the school year to 200 days to have the power to change, said Janey, who reached an agreement with his teacher union last year on 185 days a year, which he sees as a "milestone" on the way to a greater boost in the next contract.
Higher education for more people as a future outlook
The bus arrives at the Gettysburg College with a loud pipe.
Graciela Rodriguez, 12, stands out and flashes for a moment by seeing the white columns, the brick facades, and the emerald green lawn.
Graciela’s parents have barely completed high school in El Salvador.
Until recently, Graciela, who was rescued in Silver Spring and now lives in Riverdale, had never even set foot on a college campus.
Their attitude and that of the other eight-grade members of the group exploring Gettysburg, where the lessons cost $38,690 a year, was more that of a reverent visitor than that of an enthusiastic future student.
"Yes, here I will be soon!" cried Graciela, who wanted to study medicine, when the guide announced that they had now entered the building for natural sciences.
“Wow, really?” she said thoughtfully when she was about the school’s low professor-to-student ratio.
The college in Pennsylvania was the seventh that the children attended on their three-day tour, and now they have fully embraced the intended message: The question is not whether to go to college.
The question is where.
On the one hand, there is growing concern about the large number of U.S.-born children of Hispanic immigrants who fail to finish high school or become pregnant as teenagers, but on the other hand, there are hundreds of thousands who receive the college education needed to rise to the middle class.
In fact, one in five of these “second generation” Hispano-Americans graduate from college – which is a remarkable achievement as many of their immigrant parents, mostly from Mexico or Central America, came to the United States without finishing high school.
Their success stories are important, researchers say, because they show the way forward for a generation that will play a huge role in the country’s workforce.
Those who examine powerful children say they often have a natural affinity for school and an inherent drive to success.
Many of them also have parents who set high goals for their children and find ways to compensate for their lack of familiarity with American schools.
But counseling programs also play a big role in helping Graciela and millions of children like her get to college, especially if these efforts continue over a longer period of time.
If you look at low-income children whose parents don’t have the experience and skills to help them find their way through the system, then a single action at some point won’t solve the problem, said Patricia Gándara, a researcher at the University of California in Davis who studied Hispanic-American students.
We need to think about providing a support network for these children from preschool to high school.
The federal program that had funded Graciela’s college tour is a useful example.
It is known as GEAR UP – Switching A Walk Up – and provides more than $300 million a year for local school systems to launch college preparation programs that start when low-income students are in high school and continue until they have completed high school.
According to the U.S. Department of Education, the program has helped more than 10 million students since 1999, of whom more than 60% have attended college.
