Changes in aging China
Wang Weijia and her husband grew up surrounded by propaganda posters giving them lectures that "Mother Earth is too tired to entertain more children" and "A baby more means a grave more."
They learned these lessons so well that, as government officials in Shanghai, suddenly beginning to change course this summer due to the low birth rate and the ageing population, encouraging young couples to have more than one child, their response was immediate and definitive: “Not at all.”
We have already invested all our time and energy in a child.
Nothing remains for a second child, said Wang, 31, a staff manager with an 8-month-old son.
More than 30 years after the introduction of the one-child policy in China, which has produced two generations of notoriously thick, debilitated single children lovingly called "little emperors", a population crisis is rising in the country.
The average birth rate has fallen to 1.8 children per couple compared to 6 at the time this policy came into force, the UN says.
Department of Population affairs stated that while the number of the population aged 60 and older is expected to rise explosively by 2020 from 16.7 percent of the population by 2050 to 31.1 percent, this is well above the global average of about 20 percent.
The imbalance is stronger in rich coastal cities with educated populations, such as Shanghai.
Last year, 60-year-olds and older people accounted for 22 percent of residents of Shanghai, while the birth rate was below one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, head of the Shanghai Urban Population and Family Planning Commission, said couples in childbearing age need to have babies to “help reduce the ratio of aging population and alleviate the labor shortage of the future.”
"Shanghai will soon be as old -- but not as rich -- as the developed countries, such as Japan and Sweden," she said.
A gradual relaxation
Anchored in the country’s 1978 constitution, China’s one-child policy is likely to be the most controversial provision ever introduced by the ruling Communist Party.
Couples who violate this policy will face enormous fines – up to three times their annual salary in some regions – and discrimination at work.
Chinese officials have attributed this policy to avoiding critical exploitation of the country’s natural resources, while human rights activists have condemned abuses in the enforcement of the policy.
In rural areas, some officials have forced pregnant women who already had a child to evacuate.
Many couples had also had sex-selective abortions, resulting in an unnaturally high ratio of men to women.
In recent years, government representatives for the population have gradually weakened their stance on the one-child policy.
In 2004, they allowed more exceptions to the rule—including urban residents, members of ethnic minorities, and cases where both husband and wife were single children—and in 2007 the tone of many harsh slogans was softened.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Institute for Population Research at the University of Beijing, said government officials have recently even discussed more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children with one partner being single child.
In July, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to promote more births.
Posters teaching families to have only one child have been replaced almost overnight by guidelines detailing who is eligible for a second child and how to apply for permission.
The city administration has dispatched city employees and family planning volunteers to visit couples at home and scatter information sheets under the doors.
