The UN-sponsored climate conference -- which has so far been marked by wild poses and mutual accusations -- has once again placed a focus on the next 40 years with the publication of a document that records ambitious reductions in greenhouse gas emissions, with the most burden to be borne by the industrialized nations in the near future.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement on greenhouse gas regulation, has identified both the remaining obstacles and the way forward.
But it has been seen as an important step forward in a negotiation that expires time as more than 100 top politicians from around the world will arrive in Copenhagen next week.
The text, formulated by a special UN working group, silences the amount of money that rich countries should give to the poor countries so that they can cope with global warming in the short and long term.
