The process is given a lot of flexibility, says John Coequyt, senior representative of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who designed the six-page document, has compiled a 180-page negotiation text to focus on what the UN’s leading climate representative, Yvo de Boer, called “the big whole.”
It shows the basis for a possible agreement by which the industrialized nations would jointly reduce their emissions by 25 to 45 percent by 2020, compared to the 1990 limits, while larger developing countries would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent over the same period.
Together, the countries could reduce emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Community also boosted Friday’s talks with its pledge to provide $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the effects of climate change – from mastering floods and droughts to preventing deforestation.
Friday still brought the same verbal fireworks that the talks of last week had determined.
U.S. climate adviser Todd Stern has rejected formulations calling for binding reductions in greenhouse gas emissions for industrialized countries, compared to voluntary reductions for larger emerging countries, if they are not funded by industrialized nations.
This train announced that the Obama administration is driving a tougher line with China than representatives of the Bush administration did not even two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without larger emerging nations rising up and taking action, according to Stern, who also complained that the text is not going far enough to ensure that the cuts could also be confirmed by outsiders.
Stern issued his statement an hour after the statement by Chinese Deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei, who said the leading U.S. climate negotiator either lacked "reason" or it was "extremely irresponsible" from him that he said earlier this week that the United States would not financially help China cope with global warming.
By putting the future economic direction of the world’s great powers at stake, breaches have opened up both within the industrialized nations and between the industrialized nations and the emerging economies.
The current struggle relates to both saving individual economies and saving the planet, with China and the United States fighting for their respective commitments, while poorer countries claim that the two dozen most influential countries would ignore the scientific need to take more courageous action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it’s not surprising that the great powers are struggling to figure out who should bear the cost of braking greenhouse gas emissions, as even affected countries have moved to act more aggressively in holding the countries with very high greenhouse gas taxes accountable for their actions.
