The cradle of dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other meat-eating dinosaurs: The two-foot-long and 1.50-foot-high animal ran on two strong rear legs, had an alonged skull with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with seals, and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it would not be special.
But Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs to have these body characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in the journal Science of Thursday.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in today’s New Mexico, which was then located in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pangea on the equator.
Tawa opens a new window to the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It tells us a lot about the relatives, spread and characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began an excavation at the Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
We sometimes found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, which is unprecedented for deposits from the Trias, reports team member Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History.
Some of the bones were quickly identified by the researchers as new species.
During the excavation, they collected the remains of a total of five individuals.
Fund Confirms Theories About Dino Early History
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, it is an extraordinary finding: "Dinosaur fossils from the Trias are extremely rare, mostly you can only find individual fragments."
Other dinosaur experts do not necessarily share the enthusiasm.
This finding is not spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current doctrine, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
However, many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, which is why the assignment of these primitive dinosaurs is mostly controversial.
For example, the experts are debating when the squirrels split into their three main lines of development: the meat-eating theropods, which later included the Tyrannosaurus rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, the four-legged sauropods known as "longheads" and their relatives, and the plant-eating Ornithischia (bird basin sauriers), which included, for example, the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
According to Nesbitt and colleagues’ analysis, Tawa hallae is an original theropod.
He has an interesting combination of primitive and advanced qualities, says Nesbitt.
On the skull of Tawa hallae, for example, the researchers found evidence of airbags, as they also have the descendants of the theropods, the birds.
Thanks to the air bags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
In Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were also apparently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with airbags, says Randall Irmis.
Since the relative line of giant sauropods later also possessed airbags and lightweight bones, the common ancestor of the two groups had probably already produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs ever known lived in South America, the researchers conclude that the squirrels first appeared there.
Thus, the three lines of development separated from each other early on, spreading from South America to all parts of the world, which at that time, as the supercontinent Pangea, formed a single landmass.
That’s because the team, along with Tawa hallae, found the remains of two other, not closely related theropods.
The three may not descend from a common immigrant ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe there have been at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the science study.
Of course, there are also contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, belonging to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in today’s Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
In his opinion, it could result in a distorted picture, because in South America there are simply many primitive dino fossils preserved, while there is hardly anything to find on other continents.
How the dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare side line of the reptilian tribe to the dominant land vertebrates of the Middle Ages is still a mystery.
During the Trias, the dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of today's crocodiles and flysaurs and with numerous other squirrels.
Towards the end of the Trias, dinosaurs spread around the world and developed many new species, while the family extinct at the border from the Trias to the Jura.
Success story did not last forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this shift, says Martin Sander.
There may have been a mass extinction that the dinosaurs accidentally survived, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted so they could beat the competition out of the field.
The success story did not last forever.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact helped to flourish a group of animals that had also developed in the Trias and has since tempted a shadow being: the mammals.
