75% of working mothers have had problems at work because of their maternity
Discrimination in work has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who want to have children.
This is the conclusion of the study "Fertility and Careers of Women in Spain", conducted by CSIC in collaboration with the Institute for Women.
The survey of 9,737 women between the ages of 15 and 75 leaves no doubt: 75% of working women find their career opportunities on the labour market limited due to their maternity.
The study reveals that there are huge differences in the decision to start a family and the number of children depending on whether the women are working or not and, if so, what kind of profession they are exercising.
Those of them who do not do any other activity outside the house, only work half-hours or do not have a fixed employment contract are more likely to become mothers and have more children.
In contrast, women with a fixed job, especially in the public sector, delay the establishment of a family and motherhood and therefore have fewer children.
“The women in the age group between 35 and 49 with a fixed employment have their first child on average only 3.7 years after the withdrawal, a figure that rises to 4.1 years for women with a fixed employment who took longer to this and who joined and realized the first child only much later.
In addition, the type of work also has a big impact on maternity, although less than the calendar in terms of conception readiness,” explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that needs to be taken into account with the age of women in marriage and the first child.
According to the survey, the higher the age at the time of marriage and the first child, the higher the level of education.
This difference was also observed in women of the same age.
For example, the women in the group between 35 and 49 years old, depending on whether they only have a primary school degree or higher education, were on average 25.1 or 32.1 first-time mothers each.
There are also differences between women, depending on their level of education.
While women with a primary degree get married before their first fixed employment and have their first child, women with a middle or high school degree do it quite differently and first look for a fixed employment and then get married and then get their first child, Delgado notes.
