Support for braking in critical situations is now mandatory
As was the case with the anti-blocking braking system ABS and as is now the case with the stability control ESP, emergency braking assistance systems must become a mandatory feature in European cars.
In fact, they are already compulsory for all newly registered passenger cars and light trucks, and for the remaining vehicles a deadline has been set until the end of February 2011.
The measures adopted by the European Union aim to improve the protection of pedestrians, but these braking systems can also help prevent many accidents due to their functioning.
The task of the emergency braking assistant is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the event of a critical braking maneuver, which the system detects on the braking pedal based on the braking strength performed by the driver.
However, this system does not exert this pressure to the end.
According to an investigation commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, one-third of the drivers involved in an accident did not even step on the brake pedal before the collision and half of them had not slowed off with full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The braking aid, on the other hand, intervenes with maximum force in the braking system, thereby reducing the braking time and thus also the braking distance that a car passes during the braking process.
According to an EU study, up to 1,100 fatal accidents in which pedestrians are injured could be prevented each year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency braking assistants.
There would even be fewer accidents – one in four injury-related accidents could be prevented – once so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that detects obstacles (via radar or a camera) and warns the driver, while at the same time exercising a slight pressure on the brakes.
When the driver reacts, the system helps him increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is already inevitable, the Brake Assist applies maximum pressure on the brakes to keep the damage as low as possible.
