New Vehicle Assessment Programs
In these days of storms and accidents, not only car workshops earn
Every day, thousands of vehicles involved in an accident are dragged into the workshops, where an assessor must assess the damage incurred and the cost of repairs.
No single accident is the same and calculating the cost of the parts and working hours can be a lengthy and complicated task.
The calculation of repair costs of between 20,000 and 30,000 euros per hand, including parts and working hours, can take up to two or three hours.
On the other hand, with the support of the latest computer science tools, it is a matter of minutes.
That’s why almost 100% of reviewers use this type of systems.
Accident assessment and repair service and application providers collect the information they receive from manufacturers in order to process it and offer it to their customers in the form of a useful program.
In Spain, Audatex, part of the American group Solera, is the market leader; 80% of all reviews are produced with their products.
The other two companies that compete with on the tool market for reviewing and preparing a report are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with the data provided by the manufacturers is all but simple.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, Sales Manager at Audatex, 63 manufacturers and importers are working with each of them to provide the information in a different format.
Furthermore, the amount of data to be processed is growing, to the point that more versions, variants and engines have come on the market in the last five years than in the entire fifteen years before.
As soon as a new car comes on the market, work begins for the companies.
It is a tough task because every one of the thousands of vehicle parts must be cataloged and its price entered.
In addition, each model creates a “smart” graphic image on which you can “click” different parts of the vehicle.
If this is a well-sold model, the work can be completed in a week if the procedure proceeds quickly.
If it is a less common car, it can take up to three or four months.At present, Audatex has complete information on 99.2% of the cars sold in Spain.
Among the more exclusive models, for example, they have information about the Porsche models, but not about Ferrari or Lamborghini.
In terms of the fleet of vehicles on the roads, it is more than 99%.
For the purpose of carrying out the documentation work and the production of databases, Audatex has eight centers worldwide (Spain, France, Germany, the USA, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan) and each of them has specialized in specific brands.
The national headquarters is in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than a hundred technicians (usually mechanical specialists) work simultaneously with three computer monitors.
Audatex invests 90 million euros annually in the development of these databases.
Each month, they record 2.5 million data and their customers get the updates every second day.
Developing this enormous flow of information allows companies to use it in different ways and thus offer different products.
The most common use is the use for repairs and repairs, however, depending on the country, there are also tools for managing debris parts or for calculating the fault or residual value of a car.
The only company that has a guide that informs about the value of used cars in Spain is Eurotax.
Audatex does not offer this offer in Spain, but in the United States.
By browsing through the products that Audatex offers, you can easily get an overview of the type of support it provides to industry experts.
This company offers ten different tools, with the star of the products being AudaPlus, a standard solution for accident assessment for assessors.
It includes vehicles, motorcycles and light and heavy industrial vehicles.
In addition to the cost of the parts, it includes the manufacturer’s estimated repair times or the painting prices.
This tool is paid depending on the purpose of use, i.e. for each review.
The most expensive will be for customers who rarely use it, up to ten times a month, namely 5.75 euros per month.
On the other hand, any insurance company that produces thousands of reviews negotiates the price with Audatex.
With other products, such as AudaVIN, one can fully identify a vehicle and the equipment with which it ran from the assembly tape only by the chassis number.
AudaGlass deals with the vehicle discs, and AudaSubastas is an online service open to the professional market, with which one can offer for vehicles that have been declared total damage.
Their statistical service is very useful in identifying trends, performing geodemographic analyses or for the purpose of obtaining information about the deviations by brand and model.
For example, it can be used to examine how many models of a particular car brand had to go to the workshop due to failures or how many of them were involved in a serious accident in a given period of time.
Gt Motive is the only Spanish company dedicated to the development of this type of computer tools.
It distributes, among other things, Gt Estimate, which is also intended for reviewers and in the same way provides digital images, access to parts or prices and official working hours of the manufacturer.
Gt Motive is a company of the Einsa Group, founded in 1971 as a provider of services and solutions for the assessment of damage, breakdowns and maintenance of vehicles.
The GT Guide for Reviews is a reference product on the market.
They work with 24,000 users in workshops, 3,100 experts and 53 insurance companies.
Their business volume has increased by 20% annually over the last three years and in 2008 the turnover was EUR 10.8 million.
At the beginning of last year, they also started to enter the international market with the opening of an office in Paris.
Audatex was founded in Germany in 1966 and in Spain in 1979.
According to the company’s sources, 62% of its business is carried out in Europe and the rest of the world, and the remaining 38% in North and South America.
The total worldwide turnover of the Solera Group (Audatex, Sidexa, Informex ABZ, Hollander and IMS) is $557 million, 3.35 more than in 2008.
In this country, the company has revenue of 19.1 million euros, 7.2% more than in the previous year.
In 2005, the Solera Group was worth $1 billion on the stock market and today its shares are traded at a value of $2.4 billion.
Since 2007, it has been listed on the New York Stock Exchange and is part of the Standard & Poor's index.
